{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17497029","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17497029"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T09:02:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T09:02:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1459"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1459","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1459"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.8,0.04,0.02,0.01,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1459"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"84688"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1459","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1459"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1459"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68975"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"304"},{"type":"tags","id":"1206"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"11442"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5481"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5575"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"84688","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/84688"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with worsening left hip pain over five years, though she reports having had symptoms since early childhood. She recently migrated to Australia from Vietnam. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. She has an asymmetric gait favouring the left side. There is limited range of movement of the left hip in all directions. A radiograph of the pelvis is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Developmental dysplasia of the hip","Transient osteoporosis of the hip","Trochanteric bursitis","Bone metastasis","Tuberculous arthritis"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation and radiographic findings are characteristic of untreated \u003Cstrong\u003Edevelopmental dysplasia of the hip\u003C/strong\u003E. The key features include chronic hip symptoms since childhood, asymmetric gait, and radiographic evidence of a high-riding femoral head that has eroded a pseudoacetabulum in the ilium. The femoral shaft shows compensatory medial bowing. The migration history from Vietnam suggests limited access to early screening and treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransient osteoporosis of the hip\u003C/strong\u003E typically affects pregnant women or middle-aged men, presenting with acute onset pain. It would not explain this patient\u0027s lifelong symptoms or the characteristic radiographic changes seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETrochanteric bursitis\u003C/strong\u003E causes lateral hip pain that typically worsens when lying on the affected side. It is a soft tissue condition that does not cause the bony changes seen in this patient\u0027s radiograph.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBone metastasis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with more acute pain and would show lytic or sclerotic lesions on radiograph, not the structural changes of chronic hip displacement seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETuberculous arthritis\u003C/strong\u003E typically affects children and young adults in developing countries, causing juxta-articular osteopenia and peripheral erosions. The radiographic appearance and chronic history are not consistent with this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EManagement options for adult DDH depend on age and severity. In patients over 40 years with degenerative changes, total hip replacement is often the treatment of choice. Younger patients may be candidates for reconstructive procedures such as periacetabular osteotomy. Conservative management with analgesia and mobility aids may be appropriate for some patients.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Untreated developmental dysplasia of the hip (DDH) presents in adults with chronic hip pain, limping, and characteristic radiographic findings including high-riding femoral head and pseudoacetabulum formation.","Treatment options for adult  developmental dysplasia of the hip (DDH) depend on age and severity, ranging from conservative management to total hip replacement."],"references":["Lai KA, editor. Developmental dysplasia and dislocation of the hip in adults. Springer; 2018 Aug 28. Available at: https://link.springer.com/book/10.1007/978-981-13-0414-9","Imboden JB, Hellmann DB, Stone JA. Current diagnosis \u0026 treatment in rheumatology. McGraw Hill Professional; 2020 Oct 22","Alhaddad A, Gronfula AG, Alsharif TH, Khawjah AA, Alali MY, Jawad KM. An Overview of Developmental Dysplasia of the Hip and Its Management Timing and Approaches. Cureus. 2023 Sep 18;15(9):e45503. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10585185/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68975"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1459"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"16597"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"16597","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/16597"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/035f2db4-7bf5-492f-a1dc-580416f7924c.jpg","thumb